(Beginner) Quest 3: AvalancheGo APIs
Introduction
By this point, you should have a good understanding of Avalanche blockchain features and Subnets. In this quest, you will be introduced to AvalancheGo APIs and in particular, learn how to use its APIs to interact with the Avalanche network. We’ll be going through practical examples of calling APIs to the network through the use of Postman.
For queries on this quest, join our Discord, head to the #avalanche-helpdesk channel and look for this quest's post.
Learning Outcomes
By the end of this quest, you will be able to: 
  • Describe what APIs are and what they are used for
  • Describe AvalancheGo
  • Use AvalancheGo to interact with the blockchain
  • Describe the Keystore API
Deliverable
This quest has one deliverable.
  1. A screenshot of your output from your API call. Follow instructions in Step 10 for more details.

Quest Walkthrough
Step 1: Introduction to APIs
Before going into AvalancheGo APIs, let's first understand what an Application Programming Interface (API) is and how it works. Essentially, APIs are software intermediaries that allow two applications to communicate with each other. 
APIs let your product or service communicate with other products and services without having to know how they’re implemented. Think of APIs as the last layer of your product, exposing only what is necessary for others to interact with the product.

Let’s watch this video by Simply Explained to get a better understanding of what APIs are.



Learning Checklist
  • API stands for Application Programming Interface
  • APIs are mechanisms that enable two software components to communicate with each other using a set of definitions and protocols
  • It acts as a messenger between 2 systems taking requests and returning response back to a user
Step 2: Avalanche’s Public API Server
Avalanche has a public API server that allows for developers to interact with the Avalanche network without having to run a node themselves. The public API server allows users to interact and issue API calls on all three blockchains in Avalanche’s primary network - i.e. X-Chain, P-Chain and C-Chain. 
The public API server is run by several AvalancheGo nodes behind a load balancer, thus ensuring high availability and high request throughput.

Depending on the network you wish to connect to, you’ll need to change the base URL endpoint accordingly. We’ll touch more on this in later steps when we cover the practical examples. But for now, just note that the base URL endpoints for using the public API server to connect to the Avalanche Mainnet and Avalanche Fuji Testnet are as listed below:
  • Avalanche Mainnet - https://api.avax.network
  • Avalanche Fuji Testnet - https://api.avax-test.network

Note: Fuji is the Avalanche’s test network. You can use it to test your dApp or smart contract after you've developed it locally. 

In addition, to access a specific endpoint, you’ll need to append the correct endpoint to the end of the URL. Again, we’ll touch more on this in later steps, so not to worry!
Step 3: AvalancheGo APIs
AvalancheGo allows users to use the public API server to interact with the Avalanche Network. The APIs can be used to interact with the 3 blockchains (X-Chain, P-Chain and C-Chain). Looking at the link provided below, you can see that there are many possible API calls that you can make to the various blockchains.
AvalancheGo APIs Overview

If you click into any one of the sections in the link above, you’ll notice that the guide features mostly cURL commands. But what is that? 

cURL, which stands for client URL, is a command line tool that developers use to send data to and from a server. Essentially, cURL allows you to communicate with a server by specifying its location and some data to be sent to it.

Sounds familiar to what we covered in the previous quest? That’s because cURL is a frequently used tool to send API calls, hence the reason why it’s used in the AvalancheGo documentation.

However, as a fresh learner, using cURL commands in the terminal might seem like a daunting and confusing task. Because of this reason, Avalanche created a Postman collection where developers can simply download and import to issue API calls with. Thus removing the need for issuing cURL commands in the terminal. Let’s find out more about what Postman is in the next step.
Step 4: Introduction to Postman
Postman is a Graphical User Interface (GUI) that makes it easy for developers to easily issue API calls in a nicely formatted and readable manner. Another handy feature about Postman is the ability to have Collections. 
Postman Collections are a group of saved requests. Every request you send in Postman appears under the History tab of the sidebar. On a small scale, reusing requests through the history section is convenient. As your Postman usage grows, it can be time-consuming to find a particular request in your history. Instead of scrolling through your history section, you can save all your requests as a group for easier access.

The core development team behind Avalanche has created a Postman Collection for developers on Avalanche - it includes all the public API calls that are available on AvalancheGo instance, allowing developers to quickly issue commands to their node and see the response, without having to copy and paste long and complicated cURL commands.

Along with the API collection, there is also the example Avalanche environment for Postman - it defines common variables such as IP address of the node, Avalanche addresses and similar common elements of the queries. It was created to remove the need for developers needing to manually enter the above-mentioned fields multiple times, increasing the ease of the development process.
Step 5: Downloading Postman & Importing Collection
Alright enough talk, time to get our hands dirty! We’ll start by downloading the Postman application.
  1. Head to this site and download the Postman application
  2. After you have installed the application, run it. It will prompt you to create an account or log in. Create an account if you don’t have one
  3. In the ‘Workspaces’ tab at the top left corner of your screen, click on ‘Create Workspace’. Enter Stackup-Avax in the ‘Name’ field and click on ‘Create Workspace’
  4. Import a new collection by clicking on the ‘Import’ button at the top left of your screen
  5. Then click on ‘Link’ and input in https://raw.githubusercontent.com/ava-labs/avalanche-postman-collection/master/Avalanche.postman_collection.json, then click on ‘Continue’ and ‘Import’
  6. Lastly import the environment variables for this collection. Click on ‘Import’ button again and then click on ‘Link’ and input https://raw.githubusercontent.com/ava-labs/avalanche-postman-collection/master/Example-Avalanche-Environment.postman_environment.json. Same as before, import this.
  7. Now we’ll need to edit the environment variables. We can do this by clicking on the ‘Environments’ tab on the left side of your screen followed by the ‘Example-Avalanche-Environment’ button. Set the environment variables to active by hovering over Example-Avalanche-Environment text and click on the tick icon, as seen in the image below




Now that we're done downloading Postman and importing the Avalanche collection, we can begin to issue API calls to the network. 

But first, we'll need to change the baseURL. This is because the baseURL uses the end point of the mainnet by default but for this exercise, we’ll be executing the commands on the Fuji testnet instead. 

We can change the baseURL by changing its value in the ‘CURRENT VALUE’ column to https://api.avax-test.network. Refer to the image below if you are unsure. Remember to hit ‘Save’ on the top right hand corner of the page after you’re done editing.



And we’re done with the set up! Time to make some API calls and interact with the Avalanche network.
Step 6: Getting Wallet Balance on the P-Chain
Since there are three blockchains in the Avalanche Primary Network, let’s try making API calls to each of them. We’ll start off first with the P-Chain.
Head to the ‘Avalanche’ folder under the ‘Collections’ tab. Then, expand the ‘PlatformVM’ folder and press on ‘POST getBalance’. In this example, we’ll be getting the AVAX balance of a wallet address by calling a P-Chain API. 

Let’s refer to the Avalanche documentation as we do so - this is the exact API call that we’ll be making. The documentation shows the function signature of this API call such as its input parameters and expected outputs.



Back on Postman, click on the ‘Body’ tab; in the address key-value pair, change the address value to P-fuji1sj9s20adgsersxl6k0n36fc7ssr5hknaqs5d7d (refer to image above). Note that you can replace this value with any wallet address on the P-Chain to read that wallet’s balance, but for learning purposes, we’ll be sticking with this particular address so that we’ll all be getting the same output.

Alright, now we’re all set to make our first API call to the Avalanche network! Press the ‘Send’ button to issue the API call. You should get the same output as the image in ‘Expected output’. 

Awsome! We just queried information from the Avalanche network. In particular, we issued an API call and found out that the balance of that wallet address is 1000000000. Note that the balance reflected here is in nAVAX - which refers to AVAX in nano, 10-9. In other words, 1 AVAX = 1000000000 nAVAX.
Expected output
Step 7: Getting Next Block’s Base Fee on the C-Chain
For the second API call, let’s move on to the C-Chain. Here, we’ll be making an API call to get the base fee for the next block. A base fee is a transaction fee charged to users when performing any type of transaction on the blockchain. Again, you can find function signature of this API call here.
Head to the ‘Avalanche’ folder under the ‘Collections’ tab. Then, expand the ‘EVM’ folder and press on ‘POST eth_baseFee’. For this request, no parameter input is needed in the request body as this API call basically just returns a base fee for the next block. 

After sending the API call, you should get an output similar to the image in ‘Expected output’. The result is a hex value of the base fee for the next block. As the base fee may vary from block to block, your output might be a different value from the one shown in ‘Expected output’. 

If you’re curious on what the decimal value of your result is, you can search for a hexadecimal to decimal converter online to do the conversion.
Expected output
Step 8: Getting Asset Description on the X-Chain
Now, let's try making an API call to the X-Chain. Since the X-Chain is mainly in-charge of handling assets, let’s make an API call to get information about an asset.
But first, what is the definition of an asset? In the Avalanche network, AVAX is the native token of Avalanche. It’s a hard-capped, scarce asset that is used to pay for fees. However users can also create their own custom asset in Avalanche blockchain to be used for transfers as well.


Head to the ‘Avalanche’ folder under the ‘Collections’ tab. Then, expand the ‘AVM’ folder and press on ‘POST getAssetDescription’. Now head to the ‘Body’ tab and replace {{avaxAssetId}} with 2XZeTZrBmXv4buRyDuNj7odkpVH4x4B2fc7Jm3V4yLBp3NpQXf. Refer to the image above if you require a reference.

An asset Id is a string of text of an asset used to uniquely identify a particular asset. All assets have a different asset Id. Same as the earlier API call we made, you can change the asset Id to any existing asset Id of your choice to test out the API call, but we’re sticking with this one for demonstration purposes. Again, you can refer to the Avalanche documentation for this particular API call here.

Press the ‘Send’ button to issue the API call. You should get the same output as the image in ‘Expected output’. 

In the output of this API call, the symbol, name, denomination of the asset as well as the assetId are returned. This is a short description of what each of these fields represent:
  • name - name of the asset e.g. Avalanche
  • symbol - symbol of the asset, e.g. AVAX
  • denomination - the number of decimal places, e.g. if denomination is 0, 100 units of this asset is displayed as 100

And we’re done with the API calls using Postman! As you can see, AvalancheGo makes it really simple for developers to interact with the Avalanche network. Just by selecting the appropriate API and changing the input parameters, you can read information from the blockchains on Avalanche and even update information! 

In the next quest, we’ll show you how we can make these API calls programmatically by using cURL commands in your terminal, instead of using a GUI such as Postman.

Step 9: KeyStore API
Last but definitely not least, another very important concept we’ll cover before we end this quest is the concept of keystores. Every node has a built-in keystore. You might be wondering what a keystore is - well, you can guess from its name, it’s a store of keys. And not just any keys, private keys!
Clients create users on the keystore and these act as identities to be used when interacting with blockchains. Recall that in Web3, a transaction issued from a user must be signed with the user’s private key. A keystore exists only at the node level, so if you create a user on a node it exists only on that node. 

Since users that are created using a particular node’s keystore only exist on that node, we need a way to import and export their information to other nodes. This is where the Keystore API comes in! With the Keystore API, we have access to useful methods of handling users’ private keys such as creating, deleting, exporting, importing and listing users on our node. Refer to the Avalanche Documentation on Keystore API for more information.

Considerations
As you can probably tell from the paragraphs above, with keystores, it seems like the node operator has a lot of power over users that have been created using the node’s keystore. This is indeed true since the node operator has access to those users’ private keys. 

As such, it is highly recommended that you only create a keystore user on a node that you operate. Because if you created an account on another node using that node’s keystore and that node gets breached, you can lose all your tokens! Essentially, the keystore API is intended only for development and quick experimentation purposes and should not be used on Mainnet or production environments.

Lastly, a concept to note here is that of Hot Wallets. A hot wallet is a cryptocurrency wallet that is always connected to the internet and cryptocurrency network. Essentially, the keystore acts as a Hot Wallet since these private keys are always in the keystore, making it vulnerable to a node-level attack.

In a subsequent quest, we’ll be covering a useful tool called AvalancheJS that’s the recommended way for issuing transactions on the mainnet. Using AvalancheJS, your private keys do not have to be stored on the node, hence significantly reducing the risks of losing your funds since you’re no longer at risk of a node-level attack.
